'''Scott Francis McTominay''' (born 8 December 1996) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{Italian football updater|Napoli}} club [[SSC Napoli|Napoli]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].

McTominay is a graduate of [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester United's youth academy]] and made his senior debut for the club in May 2017. He went on to make more than 250 appearances for the club, winning the [[FA Cup]] and the [[EFL Cup]]. In 2024, McTominay signed for Napoli in a £25.7 million transfer; he emerged as a focal player to the club winning the [[2024–25 Serie A|Serie A]] title in his debut season, being named the league's [[Serie A Awards|Most Valuable Player]] and receiving a nomination for the [[Ballon d'Or]].

Born in England, McTominay qualified to play for Scotland through his father. He made his senior international debut in March 2018, and represented Scotland at [[UEFA Euro 2020|Euro 2020]] and [[UEFA Euro 2024|Euro 2024]].

==Club career==
===Manchester United===
====Youth career====
McTominay was associated with the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester United academy]] from the age of five after attending the club's development centre in [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]].<ref name="ManUtd">{{Cite web |first=Adam |last=Marshall |title=Who is Scott McTominay? |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2017/Apr/who-is-scott-mctominay-inside-united-youth-focus.aspx |website=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=30 April 2017 |access-date=30 April 2017 |archive-date=12 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512080202/http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2017/Apr/who-is-scott-mctominay-inside-united-youth-focus.aspx |url-status=live }}</ref> Although central midfield was viewed as his most natural position, he moved into the attack after there was a lack of an "out-and-out" centre forward in the reserve team.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Scott McTominay |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Players-And-Staff/Reserves/Scott-McTominay.aspx |website=ManUtd.com |access-date=30 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201075310/http://www.manutd.com/en/Players-And-Staff/Reserves/Scott-McTominay.aspx |archive-date=1 December 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He signed his first professional contract in July 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Joe|last=Short|title=Who is Scott McTominay? Everything you need to know about the Manchester United youngster|url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/798394/Manchester-United-news-Scott-McTominay-bench-reserves-midfielder-rating|work=Express|date=30 April 2017|access-date=30 April 2017|archive-date=20 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620231940/https://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/798394/Manchester-United-news-Scott-McTominay-bench-reserves-midfielder-rating|url-status=live}}</ref>

He made seven appearances for the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Under-18s]] between 2013 and 2015, but struggled due to his small size.<ref name="youthhawk">{{Cite web |title=Scott McTominay |url=http://youthhawk.co.uk/wiki/Scott_McTominay |website=youthhawk.co.uk |access-date=30 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812173849/http://youthhawk.co.uk/wiki/Scott_McTominay |archive-date=12 August 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> McTominay missed most of the 2014–15 season due to injuries relating to growth and development issues, growing 14 inches within two years.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Samuel |last=Luckhurst |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-utd-scott-mctominay-wiki-12965015 |title=Who is Scott McTominay? Manchester United midfielder profile |work=Manchester Evening News |date=30 April 2017 |access-date=30 April 2017 |archive-date=12 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201112015110/https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-utd-scott-mctominay-wiki-12965015 |url-status=live }}</ref>

McTominay struggled again during the 2015–16 season, making 11 appearances across the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Under-19]]s and [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Under-21]]s, but commanded a place in the team the following season with three goals in 21 games prior to his senior call-up.<ref name="youthhawk"/>

====2016–17 season====
On 30 April 2017, McTominay was named on the substitutes bench for a match against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] in the [[Premier League]]. He made his first Premier League appearance on 7 May, coming on as a substitute against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]],<ref>{{Cite news |first=Stephan |last=Shemilt |title=Manchester United 1–1 Swansea City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39682899 |publisher=BBC Sport (British Broadcasting Corporation) |date=28 April 2017 |access-date=30 April 2017 }}</ref> before starting Manchester United's final Premier League match of the season on 21 May, a 2–0 win at home to [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |title=Manchester United 2–0 Crystal Palace |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39912026 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 May 2017 |access-date=31 July 2017 |archive-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024192323/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39912026 |url-status=live }}</ref>

====2017–18 season====
[[File:Manchester United v Burton Albion, 20 September 2017 (30).jpg|thumb|upright|McTominay playing for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in 2017]]

Ahead of the [[2017–18 Manchester United F.C. season|2017–18 season]], McTominay was named as a member of Manchester United's touring party for their pre-season tour of the United States, as well as for matches against [[Vålerenga IF|Vålerenga]] and [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Gemma |last=Thompson |title=Manchester United's Tour 2017 squad |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Tour-2017/Tour-2017-News/2017/Jul/jose-mourinho-names-his-manchester-united-squad-for-Tour-2017-presented-by-Aon.aspx |website=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=9 July 2017 |access-date=31 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813020832/http://www.manutd.com/en/Tour-2017/Tour-2017-News/2017/Jul/jose-mourinho-names-his-manchester-united-squad-for-Tour-2017-presented-by-Aon.aspx |archive-date=13 August 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the match against Vålerenga on 30 July 2017, McTominay came on as a substitute for [[Paul Pogba]] just after the hour mark, and 10 minutes later, he scored his first senior goal for the club – the third in a 3–0 win.<ref>{{cite news |first=Joe |last=Ganley |title=Valerenga 0 Manchester United 3 |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Fixtures-And-Results/Match-Reports/2017/Jul/Match-report-Valerenga-v-Manchester-United-Tour-2017-30-July.aspx |website=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=30 July 2017 |access-date=31 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730224611/http://www.manutd.com/en/Fixtures-And-Results/Match-Reports/2017/Jul/Match-report-Valerenga-v-Manchester-United-Tour-2017-30-July.aspx |archive-date=30 July 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> McTominay made his first appearance of the season against [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] in the [[EFL Cup]] on 20 September 2017, replacing [[Marcus Rashford]] in the 64th minute, in a 4–1 victory.<ref>{{cite news |first=Neil |last=Johnston |title=Manchester United 4–1 Burton Albion |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41249725 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 September 2017 |access-date=20 October 2017 |archive-date=14 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210114153411/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41249725 |url-status=live }}</ref>

McTominay made his European debut on 18 October, against [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]], coming on for [[Henrikh Mkhitaryan]] in injury-time, winning a free-kick and getting [[Luisão]] sent off before seeing out the 1–0 away win.<ref>{{cite news |first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |title=Benfica 0–1 Manchester United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41624728 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=18 October 2017 |access-date=20 October 2017 |archive-date=20 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210620124210/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41624728 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two days later, McTominay signed a new contract with United, keeping him at the club until June 2021, with an option to extend for a further year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Scott McTominay signs new contract at United |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2017/Oct/scott-mctominay-is-rewarded-with-new-contract-at-united.aspx |website=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=20 October 2017 |access-date=30 October 2017 |archive-date=24 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124173111/http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2017/Oct/scott-mctominay-is-rewarded-with-new-contract-at-united.aspx |url-status=live }}</ref> He made his first start of the season on 24 October, in a 2–0 win over Swansea at [[Liberty Stadium]] in the EFL Cup fourth round.<ref>{{cite news |first=Dafydd |last=Pritchard |title=Swansea City 0–2 Manchester United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41647091 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 October 2017 |access-date=30 October 2017 |archive-date=14 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210114153311/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41647091 |url-status=live }}</ref>

====2018–19 season====
On 21 January 2019, McTominay signed a contract extension, keeping him at United until 2023, with the option of another year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11667/11613825/scott-mctominay-signs-new-manchester-united-contract|title=Scott McTominay signs new Manchester United contract|date=21 January 2019|work=Sky Sports|access-date=21 January 2019|archive-date=23 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210423133847/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11667/11613825/scott-mctominay-signs-new-manchester-united-contract|url-status=live}}</ref> Replacing the injured [[Nemanja Matić]], his first start of real significance under the management of [[Ole Gunnar Solskjær]] was against Liverpool on 24 February.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/club/manchester-united/360/blog/post/3787696/scott-mctominay-takes-the-chance-to-show-his-worth-at-manchester-united |title=Scott McTominay takes the chance to show his worth at Manchester United |first=Andy |last=Mitten |date=1 March 2019 |access-date=7 March 2019 |archive-date=8 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190308081024/http://www.espn.co.uk/football/club/manchester-united/360/blog/post/3787696/scott-mctominay-takes-the-chance-to-show-his-worth-at-manchester-united |url-status=live }}</ref> McTominay was praised by pundits and reporters for his contributions in Champions League matches against [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/psg-vs-man-utd-result-score-var-penalty-hand-ball-fred-scott-mctominay-midfield-injury-ole-gunnar-solskjaer-a8811486.html|title=Scott McTominay and Fred transform United's big weakness into their strength|date=7 March 2019|website=The Independent|access-date=14 November 2020|archive-date=17 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210617100445/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/psg-vs-man-utd-result-score-var-penalty-hand-ball-fred-scott-mctominay-midfield-injury-ole-gunnar-solskjaer-a8811486.html|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]].<ref name=critch>{{Cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/manchester-united-vs-barcelona-celebration-061745232.html|title=Manchester United vs Barcelona: A celebration of Scott McTominay, the McTominator enjoying a McTomaissance|website=news.yahoo.com |date=11 April 2019 }}</ref> He scored his first competitive goal for United on 2 April 2019 in what was his 41st appearance for the club as they lost 2–1 to [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47701934|title=Wolves 2–1 Manchester United|last=Emons|first=Michael|date=2 April 2019|website=BBC Sport|access-date=2 April 2019|archive-date=23 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210423135534/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47701934|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2019–20 season====
McTominay scored his first goal at [[Old Trafford]] in a 1–1 draw against Arsenal on 30 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nottheoldfirm.com/analysis/scotland-international-and-manchester-united-star-mctominay-nets-his-first-old-trafford-goal/|title=Scotland international and Manchester United star McTominay nets his first Old Trafford goal|access-date=1 October 2019|website=NOT the old firm|date=October 2019|archive-date=4 April 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404120038/https://www.nottheoldfirm.com/analysis/scotland-international-and-manchester-united-star-mctominay-nets-his-first-old-trafford-goal/|url-status=live}}</ref> On 27 October, McTominay scored United's 2,000th Premier League goal in a 3–1 victory against [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] at [[Carrow Road]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/man-united-hit-2000-premier-league-goal-landmark|first=Adam|last=Marshall|title=Man United hit 2000 Premier League goal landmark|website=ManUtd.com|publisher=Manchester United|language=en|access-date=27 October 2019|date=27 October 2019|archive-date=26 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201026140423/https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/man-united-hit-2000-premier-league-goal-landmark|url-status=live}}</ref> McTominay was credited with another goal, scored against Brighton on 10 November, after United successfully appealed to a Premier League panel that it should not be designated as an own goal by [[Davy Pröpper]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/scott-mctominay-awarded-second-goal-in-uniteds-3-1-win-over-brighton|first=Sam|last=Carney|title=McTominay Awarded Goal During Brighton Victory|website=ManUtd.com|publisher=Manchester United|language=en|access-date=27 October 2019|date=13 November 2019|archive-date=9 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200809211143/https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/scott-mctominay-awarded-second-goal-in-uniteds-3-1-win-over-brighton|url-status=live}}</ref>

McTominay suffered a knee ligament injury on 26 December, which prevented him from playing for two months.<ref name = "knee ligament"/> He resumed full training on 19 February 2020.<ref name = "knee ligament">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51559639 |title=Scott McTominay: Scotland midfielder returns to Manchester United training |first=Simon |last=Stone |website=BBC Sport |date=19 February 2020 |access-date=19 February 2020 |archive-date=18 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200718005614/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51559639 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 27 February, McTominay scored his first European goal in United's [[UEFA Europa League]] Round of 32 second leg match against [[Club Brugge KV|Club Brugge]], with United winning 5–0 (6–1 on aggregate).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-from-man-utd-v-club-brugge-27-february-2020|first=Stuart|last=Mathieson|title=Manchester United clinically steamrollered Club Brugge 5-0 at Old Trafford to send us through to the last 16 of the Europa League|website=Manutd.com|publisher=Manchester United|access-date=27 February 2020|date=27 February 2020|archive-date=17 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201117151628/https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-from-man-utd-v-club-brugge-27-february-2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 8 March, he scored United's second goal in a 2–0 win at home to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], shooting into an empty net from 40 yards after a mistake by goalkeeper [[Ederson (footballer, born 1993)|Ederson]], to help United to their first league double over their city rivals in a decade.<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Man Utd 2-0 Man City: Anthony Martial and Scott McTominay score in derby win |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51693762 |website=BBC Sport |date=8 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-date=27 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200627074146/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51693762 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 23 June 2020, McTominay signed a new contract with Manchester United to keep him at the club until June 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/scott-mctominay-signs-new-long-term-contract-at-man-utd|title=McTominay signs long-term United contract|website=www.manutd.com|access-date=23 June 2020|archive-date=1 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200701033245/https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/scott-mctominay-signs-new-long-term-contract-at-man-utd|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== 2020–21 season ====
On 30 September 2020, McTominay scored his first goal of the season as United won 3–0 against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] in the EFL Cup.<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=Dawkes |title=Brighton 0-3 Man Utd: Paul Pogba strikes as United reach Carabao Cup quarters |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54298218 |work=BBC Sport |date=30 September 2020 |access-date=30 September 2020 |archive-date=30 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201030021628/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54298218 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 20 December 2020, he scored his first league goals of the season, when he scored a brace inside 3 minutes in a 6–2 home win against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Matthew |last=Howarth |title=Manchester United 6-2 Leeds United: Hosts up to third after thumping win |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55291044 |work=BBC Sport |date=20 December 2020 |access-date=20 December 2020 |archive-date=20 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201220164623/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55291044 |url-status=live }}</ref> This was the first time in the history of the Premier League that a player had scored twice in the opening three minutes of a game.<ref>{{cite news|title=Quickfire! McTominay, Leao set new standards among football's fastest goals|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/blog-the-toe-poke/story/4270681/quickfire!-mctominayleao-set-new-standards-among-footballs-fastest-goals|access-date=25 December 2020|work=ESPN|first=Chris|last=Wright|date=21 December 2020|archive-date=21 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201221180119/https://www.espn.co.uk/football/blog-the-toe-poke/story/4270681/quickfire!-mctominayleao-set-new-standards-among-footballs-fastest-goals|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 9 January 2021, McTominay became the stand-in captain in the FA Cup game against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] and subsequently scored the only goal of the game inside five minutes as United won 1–0.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stone |first=Simon |title=Man Utd 1-0 Watford: Scott McTominay heads early FA Cup winner at Old Trafford |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/55574516 |access-date=9 January 2021 |work=BBC Sport |date=9 January 2021 |archive-date=24 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210124043256/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/55574516 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 2 February 2021, McTominay scored a goal in Manchester United's Premier League record-equalling [[Manchester United F.C. 9–0 Southampton F.C.|9–0]] home win against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stone|first=Simon|date=2 February 2021|title=Man Utd beat nine-man Southampton 9-0|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55806211|access-date=3 February 2021|archive-date=15 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210815214453/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55806211|url-status=live}}</ref> Four days later, he followed this up by scoring in a 3–3 draw against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], making this his highest scoring season so far with six goals.<ref>{{cite news |first=Simon |last=Stone |title=Manchester United 3-3 Everton: Dominic Calvert-Lewin scores late goal to deny hosts |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55867139 |work=BBC Sport |date=6 February 2021 |access-date=6 February 2021 |archive-date=5 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210205143832/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55867139 |url-status=live }}</ref>

====2021–22 season====
[[File:Manchester United v Brighton & Hove Albion, 7 August 2022 (26) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|McTominay playing for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in 2022]]

On 30 December 2021, McTominay scored his first goal of the season when opened the scoring in a 3–1 win over [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Simon |last=Stone |title=Manchester United 3-1 Burnley: Cristiano Ronaldo on target as hosts move into top six |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59764946 |website=BBC Sport |date=30 December 2021 |accessdate=30 December 2021 |archive-date=19 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230419103526/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59764946 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 10 January 2022, McTominay scored a goal against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] to help Manchester United advance into the fourth round of the [[2021–22 FA Cup]].<ref>{{Cite news |first=Simon |last=Stone |title=Manchester United 1-0 Aston Villa: McTominay the difference for Red Devils against Villa |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59945468 |website=BBC Sport |date=10 January 2022 |accessdate=10 January 2022 |archive-date=6 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230406152240/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59945468 |url-status=live }}</ref>

====2022–23 season====
McTominay started games less frequently for United during the [[2022–23 Manchester United F.C. season|2022–23 season]] than in previous years, following the signing of [[Casemiro]] as their first choice defensive midfielder.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-united-scott-mctominay-newcastle-26585827 |title=Erik ten Hag must resist Scott McTominay temptation at Newcastle |first=Steven |last=Railston |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |date=30 March 2023 |accessdate=30 March 2023 |archive-date=18 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230418113418/https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-united-scott-mctominay-newcastle-26585827 |url-status=live }}</ref> He won his first senior trophy on 26 February 2023, appearing as a substitute in the second half of the [[2023 EFL Cup final]] against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref name = 2023EFL/>

====2023–24 season====

On 7 October 2023, after coming on as a substitute in the 87th minute, McTominay scored twice in stoppage time to give United a 2–1 comeback win against [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66969161|title=Manchester United 2-1 Brentford|date=7 October 2023|publisher=BBC Sport|archive-date=5 November 2023|access-date=7 October 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231105014343/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66969161|url-status=live}}</ref> On 29 November he scored his first [[UEFA Champions League]] goal away against [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] in a 3–3 draw, before scoring a brace in the Premier League to beat Chelsea 2–1 the following week.

On 17 December, McTominay captained Manchester United for the first time in a Premier League match in a 0–0 draw with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] at [[Anfield]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/scott-mctominay-reacts-to-captaincy-honour-and-draw-against-liverpool-at-anfield|title=MCTOMINAY OPENS UP ON CAPTAINCY HONOUR|date=17 December 2023|website=Manchester United F.C.|access-date=18 December 2023|archive-date=13 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240613170134/https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/scott-mctominay-reacts-to-captaincy-honour-and-draw-against-liverpool-at-anfield|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 11 February 2024, McTominay scored the winning goal in a 2–1 away win against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] at [[Villa Park]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/13066910/aston-villa-1-2-man-utd-scott-mctominays-late-winner-blows-race-for-champions-league-football-wide-open|title=Aston Villa 1-2 Man Utd: Scott McTominay's late winner blows race for Champions League football wide open|date=11 February 2024|access-date=12 February 2024|work=Sky Sports|last=Blitz|first=Sam|archive-date=5 September 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240905171855/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/13066910/aston-villa-1-2-man-utd-scott-mctominays-late-winner-blows-race-for-champions-league-football-wide-open|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 17 March 2024, McTominay scored the opening goal and assisted an extra-time equaliser from [[Marcus Rashford]] in a dramatic 4–3 win against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the [[FA Cup]] quarter-finals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/mar/17/manchester-united-liverpool-fa-cup-match-report|title=Manchester United edge Liverpool in FA Cup thriller as Amad Diallo strikes late|date=17 March 2024|access-date=15 July 2024|work=The Guardian|last=Hytner|first=David|archive-date=9 September 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240909130830/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/mar/17/manchester-united-liverpool-fa-cup-match-report|url-status=live}}</ref> In the following semi-final against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], McTominay scored again to give United a 1–0 lead in the 23rd minute.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/apr/21/manchester-united-coventry-fa-cup-semi-final-match-report|title=Manchester Utd survive epic Coventry comeback to reach FA Cup final|date=22 April 2024|access-date=15 July 2024|work=The Guardian|last=Jackson|first=Jamie|archive-date=9 May 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240509015934/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/apr/21/manchester-united-coventry-fa-cup-semi-final-match-report|url-status=live}}</ref>
In the [[2024 FA Cup final|FA Cup final]], McTominay started as United beat rivals [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] 2–1.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/article/2024/may/25/manchester-city-manchester-united-fa-cup-final-match-report|title=Manchester United win FA Cup after Garnacho and Mainoo stun City|date=26 May 2024|access-date=15 July 2024|work=The Guardian|last=Hytner|first=David}}</ref>

===Napoli===

==== 2024–25 season ====
On 30 August 2024, McTominay ended a seven-year run with Manchester United and joined [[Serie A]] club [[SSC Napoli|Napoli]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Marra |first=Bruno |date=30 August 2024 |title=Scott McTominay officially joins Napoli |url=https://sscnapoli.it/en/il-napoli-ufficializza-lacquisto-di-scott-mctominay/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240831092411/https://sscnapoli.it/en/il-napoli-ufficializza-lacquisto-di-scott-mctominay/ |archive-date=31 August 2024 |access-date=2 September 2024 |publisher=SSC Napoli}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=30 August 2024 |title=Scott McTominay completes move to Napoli |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/Scott-McTominay-completes-move-from-Man-Utd-to-Napoli |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240901111238/https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/Scott-McTominay-completes-move-from-Man-Utd-to-Napoli |archive-date=1 September 2024 |access-date=30 August 2024 |publisher=Manchester United}}</ref> The deal was reportedly worth £25.7 million.<ref>{{cite news |date=30 August 2024 |title=Scott McTominay: Manchester United and Scotland midfielder joins Napoli |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cdx6g3vy514o |access-date=30 August 2024 |work=BBC Sport |archive-date=30 August 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240830192204/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cdx6g3vy514o |url-status=live }}</ref> On 26 September, he scored his first goal in a 5–0 win over [[Derby delle Due Sicilie]] rivals [[Palermo FC|Palermo]] in the [[2024–25 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]].<ref>{{cite web |date=26 September 2024 |title=Napoli 5–0 Palermo: Scott McTominay scores in Coppa Italia win |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cn0ejxgvjz4t |work=BBC Sport |access-date=4 October 2024 |archive-date=3 October 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241003063928/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cn0ejxgvjz4t |url-status=live }}</ref>
On 4 October, McTominay scored his first Serie A goal, scoring in just 25 seconds in a 3–1 win over [[Como 1907|Como]].<ref>{{cite web |date=4 October 2024 |title=Napoli vs Como: Serie A |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cm2487ppgdet |work=BBC Sport|access-date=4 October 2024 |archive-date=5 October 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241005004542/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cm2487ppgdet |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 27 April 2025, he scored both goals in a 2–0 victory against Torino to put Napoli at the top of the Serie A table.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/ckgr3nn2x66t|title=Serie A: Scott McTominay double sends leaders Napoli three points clear|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> McTominay's five league goals in April saw him named [[Serie A Player of the Month]], becoming the first Scottish player to win the award.<ref name="POTM">{{cite press release|url=https://www.legaseriea.it/en/media/serie-a/scott-mctominay-ea-sports-fc-player-of-the-month-for-april|title=Scott McTominay "EA Sports FC Player of the Month" for April|access-date=8 May 2025|date=8 May 2025|publisher=Serie A}}</ref>

On 23 May, McTominay scored Napoli's first goal, a stunning acrobatic kick<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://onefootball.com/de/news/video-acrobatic-mctominay-puts-napoli-within-touching-distance-of-serie-a-title-41153030|title=Video: Acrobatic McTominay puts Napoli within touching distance of Serie A title|date=23 May 2025|website=OneFootball}}</ref> against [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]] as they won 2–0 to secure the club's fourth Serie A title. He also won the Serie A MVP award for the [[2024–25 SSC Napoli season|2024–25 season]], as well as being included in the Serie A Team of the Season,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sscnapoli.it/en/il-napoli-premiato-al-gran-gala-del-calcio/|title=Napoli collect four awards at Gran Galà del Calcio|first=Bruno|last=Marra|date=2 December 2025|publisher=SSC Napoli}}</ref> marking his first season for the club as a success.<ref name="CBS">{{cite web |title=Napoli down Cagliari, win 2024-25 Serie A title: Antonio Conte wins the Scudetto in his first year at the club |first=Francesco |last=Porzio|url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/napoli-down-cagliari-win-2024-25-serie-a-title-antonio-conte-wins-the-scudetto-in-his-first-year-at-the-club/|work=CBS Sports |access-date=23 May 2025|date=23 May 2025}}</ref>

Following his first season, [[BBC Sport]] described McTominay as a "fan favourite" and "Napoli icon" with images of him having quickly become some of the most popular displayed around Naples. He had also gained the nickname "McFratm" (the literal translation of "McBrother") by the Napoli fanbase.<ref>{{cite news|title=Scott McTominay: How the Scotland midfielder became a Napoli icon|first=Emlyn|last=Begley|date=11 May 2025|publisher=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c75d25rp0dyo}}</ref> He received a nomination for the prestigious [[Ballon d'Or]] award for his performances in the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/ballondor/news/029c-1e6c441438f3-f4ffe2b42288-1000--2025-ballon-d-or-awards-nominees-revealed/|title=2025 Ballon d'Or awards nominees revealed|website=UEFA}}</ref>

==== 2025–26: Serie A runner-up ====
On 23 August 2025, the first Serie A matchday of the season, McTominay scored the first Napoli goal in this season via a header in the 34th minute against [[US Sassuolo Calcio|Sassuolo]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Sassuolo VS Napoli |url=https://www.legaseriea.it/en/match/2025-26-sassuolo-napoli-serie-a-matchday-1 |access-date=8 November 2025 |website=www.legaseriea.it}}</ref> Two months later on 25 October 2025, he scored against rivals [[Inter Milan]] to put Napoli at the top of the Serie A table via a first touch volley into the bottom corner.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Napoli VS Internazionale |url=https://www.legaseriea.it/en/match/2025-26-napoli-internazionale-serie-a-matchday-8 |access-date=8 November 2025 |website=www.legaseriea.it}}</ref> That goal was later credited as the [[Serie A Goal of the Month]]  October 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Awards {{!}} Serie A |url=https://www.legaseriea.it/en/serie-a/award |access-date=8 November 2025 |website=www.legaseriea.it}}</ref>
On 22 December 2025 McTominay was part of the Napoli team that beat Bologna 2–0 to win the [[2025–26 Supercoppa Italiana]] held in [[Saudi Arabia|Riyadh]].<ref>{{Cite web |title= Neres double as Napoli outclass Bologna to win Italian Super Cup |url= https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/neres-double-napoli-outclass-bologna-win-italian-super-cup-2025-12-22/ |access-date=29 December 2025 |website=www.reuters.com}}</ref>

==International career==
===Eligibility===
McTominay was born in England but qualifies for Scotland through his father, who is from [[Helensburgh]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.helensburghadvertiser.co.uk/sport/16075887.football-manchester-uniteds-scott-mctominay-delights-helensburgh-family-scotland-decision/|title=Football: Manchester United's Scott McTominay delights his Helensburgh family with Scotland decision|last=Borland|first=Craig|date=9 March 2018|work=Helensburgh Advertiser|access-date=18 October 2024}}</ref><ref name=helens>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenational.scot/sport/17507147.alex-mcleish-scott-mctominay-can-be-a-scotland-great-but-fans-shouldnt-expect-george-best/ |title=Alex McLeish: Scott McTominay can be a Scotland great – but fans shouldn't expect George Best |last=Lindsay |first=Matthew |work=The National |date=18 March 2019 }}</ref> McTominay attended training camps with the Scottish youth sides. In November 2017, McTominay told [[Scottish Football Association]] performance director [[Malky Mackay]] that he wanted to concentrate on securing a place in the Manchester United first team.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41890205 |title=Scotland: Scott McTominay yet to decide on his international future |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=6 November 2017 |access-date=7 November 2017 |archive-date=5 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405200256/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41890205 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Speaking in February 2018, club manager [[José Mourinho]] suggested that new Scotland manager [[Alex McLeish]] should select McTominay "because it looks like England is missing him".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43105205 |title=Manchester United's Jose Mourinho says Scott McTominay deserves Scotland call |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=18 February 2018 |access-date=18 February 2018 |archive-date=19 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230419091928/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43105205 |url-status=live }}</ref> McTominay pledged his future to Scotland and was selected in their squad for two friendlies in March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43279384|title=Scott McTominay: Man Utd midfielder pledges international future to Scotland|date=4 March 2018|website=BBC Sport|access-date=27 August 2019|first=Simon|last=Stone|archive-date=5 April 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405063951/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43279384|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43369364 |title=Six new faces in Alex McLeish's Scotland squad for March friendlies |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=12 March 2018 |access-date=12 March 2018 |archive-date=15 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201115060846/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43369364 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later that month, McTominay's grandfather said that [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] wanted him to represent Scotland. Manchester United academy coach [[Brian McClair]] explained "McLeish made a huge effort getting to [[Trafford Training Centre|Carrington]] to meet up with him, because it was in the middle of the bad weather that we had. He made it, put a case. [[Gareth Southgate]] sent him a text."<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/club/scotland/580/blog/post/3427665/scott-mctominay-choosing-scotland-over-england-was-a-no-brainer|title=Choosing Scotland easy for McTominay|work=ESPN.com|access-date=24 March 2018|archive-date=4 April 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404184344/https://www.espn.co.uk/football/club/scotland/580/blog/post/3427665/scott-mctominay-choosing-scotland-over-england-was-a-no-brainer|url-status=live}}</ref> McTominay said of the conversation with McLeish, "He travelled a hell of a long way to come and speak with me and I have to thank him for that. The conversation we had was relatively simple. I wanted to play for Scotland and I always have done since I was a young boy and it was an incredibly proud moment for me when he did call me up and hopefully I can kick on and do well."<ref name=costa>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V39oszkkuM0|title=Scott McTominay Interview &#124; Scotland v Costa Rica|date=20 March 2018 |via=www.youtube.com|access-date=11 April 2019|archive-date=7 April 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230407235441/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V39oszkkuM0|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Debut===
On 23 March, McTominay was one of four players to be given their international debuts in McLeish's first game in charge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/scotland-defeated-1-0-by-costa-rica/?rid=14258|title=Scotland v Costa Rica {{!}} Match Report {{!}} Scottish FA|website=www.scottishfa.co.uk|language=en|access-date=23 March 2018|archive-date=4 April 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404053316/https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/scotland-defeated-1-0-by-costa-rica/?rid=14258|url-status=live}}</ref> He played the first 57 minutes in a 1–0 friendly defeat to [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]] before being replaced by [[Stuart Armstrong]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43380252|title=Scotland 0–1 Costa Rica|date=23 March 2018|work=BBC Sport|access-date=23 March 2018|archive-date=5 April 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405063954/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43380252|url-status=live}}</ref> He made his first competitive appearance for Scotland in September 2018, as a 79th minute substitute for [[Callum McGregor]] in a 2–0 win against Albania.<ref name=sfa/> He was selected for international duty again in November 2019, but had to withdraw due to injury.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/scotland/50389854|title=Scotland: Andy Robertson, Ryan Fraser and Scott McTominay withdraw from squad|work=BBC Sport|date=12 November 2019|archive-date=12 November 2019|access-date=12 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112104223/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/scotland/50389854|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Euro 2020===
For the international games played in September 2020, McTominay was used as a centre-back in a three-man defence by head coach [[Steve Clarke]].<ref name = Sep2020/> ''The Times'' commented that McTominay had the physique needed for the position, but had struggled to adapt to the role.<ref name = Sep2020>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.com/article/talking-points-scott-mctominay-struggles-in-central-defence-djf7vrz9q |title=Talking points: Scott McTominay struggles in central defence |first=Paul |last=Forsyth |newspaper=[[The Times]] |date=8 September 2020 |access-date=9 October 2020 |archive-date=26 January 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250126171121/https://www.thetimes.com/article/talking-points-scott-mctominay-struggles-in-central-defence-djf7vrz9q |url-status=live }}</ref> He continued in this role during the October 2020 internationals, and the ''Daily Record'' said that there were indications that his play had improved.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/steve-clarkes-scotland-hard-watch-22829180 |title=Steve Clarke's Scotland may be hard to watch but they're grinding teams into submission - Keith Jackson's big match verdict |first=Keith |last=Jackson |newspaper=Daily Record |date=12 October 2020 |access-date=12 October 2020 |archive-date=7 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230407050939/https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/steve-clarkes-scotland-hard-watch-22829180 |url-status=live }}</ref> He converted his penalties in the shootouts against [[Israel national football team|Israel]] and in the final playoff against [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]], helping Scotland qualify for [[UEFA Euro 2020]], their first tournament in 23 years.

McTominay was named in the squad for the Euro 2020 finals.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Man United boost as McTominay named in Scotland Euro 2020 squad|url=https://theworldnews.net/gb-news/man-united-boost-as-mctominay-named-in-scotland-euro-2020-squad|website=The World News|access-date=6 October 2021|archive-date=6 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211006051643/https://theworldnews.net/gb-news/man-united-boost-as-mctominay-named-in-scotland-euro-2020-squad|url-status=live}}</ref> He started all three [[UEFA Euro 2020 Group D|Group D]] games against the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]], [[England national football team|England]] and [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]]; however, Scotland failed to qualify for the knockout stages.

===2022 World Cup qualification===
McTominay scored his first international goal on 9 October 2021, an injury-time winner against [[Israel national football team|Israel]] in a [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group F|2022 World Cup qualifier]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/oct/09/scotland-israel-world-cup-qualifying-match-report |title=Scott McTominay's late strike caps Scotland's thrilling win over Israel |first=Ewan |last=Murray |work=The Guardian |date=9 October 2021 |accessdate=10 October 2021 |archive-date=5 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405234754/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/oct/09/scotland-israel-world-cup-qualifying-match-report |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Euro 2024 qualification ===

On 25 March 2023 McTominay scored two late goals in a 3–0 win over [[Cyprus national football team|Cyprus]] in the first game of [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64997970 |title=Scotland 3–0 Cyprus |work=BBC Sport |date=25 March 2023 |access-date=29 March 2023 |archive-date=31 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230331212623/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64997970 |url-status=live }}</ref> Three days later he scored another brace in a 2–0 win over [[Spain national football team|Spain]], his country's first win against that opponent since 1984.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65022207 |title=Scotland 2–0 Spain |work=BBC Sport |date=28 March 2023 |access-date=28 March 2023 |archive-date=12 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230412060447/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65022207 |url-status=live }}</ref> McTominay scored his fifth goal of the qualifying group during a 2–0 win against [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]] in June 2023.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65969204 |title=Scott McTominay: Unloved at Man Utd, adored by Scotland |website=BBC Sport |first=Tom |last=English |date=20 June 2023 |accessdate=22 June 2023 |archive-date=15 August 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230815160813/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65969204 |url-status=live }}</ref> He then scored the first goal in a 3–0 away win at Cyprus, while also providing an assist for fellow midfielder [[John McGinn]]. He ended the qualification phase as Scotland's top-scorer with seven goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/news/027f-17a4d90bd6fa-7e788a38951f-1000--euro-2024-qualifying-top-scorers-romelu-lukaku-races-clear/|title=EURO 2024 qualifying top scorers: Romelu Lukaku races clear of competition|date=20 November 2023|website=UEFA}}</ref>

=== Euro 2024 ===
On 7 June 2024, McTominay was named in Scotland's squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2024]] finals in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/record-breaking-goalkeeper-gordon-out-scotland-euro-2024-squad-2024-06-07/|title=Record-breaking goalkeeper Gordon out of Scotland's Euro 2024 squad|date=7 June 2024|access-date=15 June 2024|website=Reuters|archive-date=10 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240610103827/https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/record-breaking-goalkeeper-gordon-out-scotland-euro-2024-squad-2024-06-07/|url-status=live}}</ref> A week later, he started the opening match of the tournament as Scotland lost 5–1 to hosts [[Germany national football team|Germany]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c844x4y3ee3t|title=Ruthless Germany humble 10-man Scotland in Euro 2024 opener|website=BBC Sport|date=14 June 2024|access-date=15 June 2024|archive-date=6 July 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240706061452/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c844x4y3ee3t|url-status=live}}</ref> it was his [[Scottish FA International Roll of Honour|50th international appearance]] (teammate [[Ryan Christie]] also reached the milestone).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b2203012638-25d41b72cf92-1000--germany-5-1-scotland-hosts-hit-ground-running-in-munich/|title=Germany 5-1 Scotland: Hosts hit ground running in Munich|website=[[UEFA]]|date=14 June 2024|access-date=6 September 2024|archive-date=18 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240618045038/https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b2203012638-25d41b72cf92-1000--germany-5-1-scotland-hosts-hit-ground-running-in-munich/|url-status=live}}</ref> On 19 June, he scored Scotland's goal (aided by a deflection from [[Fabian Schär]]) as they got their first point in a 1–1 draw in their second group match against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] in [[Cologne]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Wright |first=Nick |date=19 June 2024 |title=Euro 2024 - Scotland 1-1 Switzerland: Scott McTominay on target as Steve Clarke's side keep knockout hopes alive |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/scotland-vs-switzerland/report/500393 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240619231250/https://www.skysports.com/football/scotland-vs-switzerland/report/500393 |archive-date=19 June 2024 |access-date=19 June 2024 |website=[[Sky Sports]]}}</ref> Aside from [[Antonio Rüdiger]]'s own goal in the opening game, Scotland scored no other goals in the tournament as they were defeated 1–0 by [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] in their third group game, in which McTominay played all 90 minutes.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Scotland 0-1 Hungary: Euro 2024 over for Steve Clarke's side after stoppage-time goal |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c899z89p7d4t |date=24 June 2024 |access-date=11 July 2024 |website=BBC Sport |archive-date=11 July 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240711203742/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c899z89p7d4t |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== 2026 World Cup qualification ===
On 18 November 2025, Scotland faced [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] at [[Hampden Park|Hampden]] in their final [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2026 World Cup qualifier]], needing a win to qualify automatically. McTominay opened the scoring in the third minute with a stunning [[bicycle kick]], a move which commentator [[Steven Thompson (Scottish footballer)|Steven Thompson]] compared to [[basketball]] player [[Michael Jordan]].<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1990871517870149871|user=BBCSportScot|author=BBC Sport Scotland|title=MCTOMINAY!! 🏴󠁧󠁢󠁳󠁣󠁴󠁿<br/>UNBELIEVABLE! 😲<br/>#BBCFootball}}</ref> The game finished 4–2 to Scotland, marking their first World Cup qualification since [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cew4v8vgkyyo|title=World Cup qualifying: 'Scotland cash in almost 30 years of glorious failure as dreams come true'|last=McPheat|first=Nick|date=18 November 2025|website=BBC Sport|access-date=18 November 2025}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Primarily a midfielder, McTominay started in a more defensive role earlier in his career for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], being utilised by [[José Mourinho]] and [[Ole Gunnar Solskjær]] as a holding midfielder alongside [[Fred (footballer, born 1993)|Fred]]. Despite being enrolled in this position, McTominay is known for his ability to score goals from runs into the box, headers and volleys, as well as his physical defensive play and aerial ability. Since transferring to Napoli, he has been enrolled in an attacking role, becoming one of their dominant attacking forces in the process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c75d25rp0dyo|title=Scott McTominay: How the Scotland midfielder became a Napoli icon|date=11 May 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

